Charge separation was quantified by analyzing the decay kinetics of the polaron PIA bands (Fig. 7c). The decay profile was observed at 750 ≤ λ ≤ 810 nm, where the broad PIAs of the CT states and of the free charges overlapped. In this wavelength range, the molar absorption coefficients of the CT states and the free charges were the same; therefore, the total PIA signal intensity was simply proportional to the sum of the concentrations of the CT states and free charges38,51. A simple model suggested by Massip et al. was then used to analyze the decay kinetics52. This model considered the situation in which the free charges were generated by separation of the CT states as the remaining nondissociated CT states recombined to the ground state. Nongeminate recombination of the free charges was neglected because the model considered the 1–1000 ps timescale, which was too short for nongeminate recombination to occur. This model considered exactly the same situation that we considered and therefore was applied in our analyses without modification. According to the kinetic model, the concentrations of the CT states and free charges could be written as follows:2d[CT]dt=-(ks+kr)[CT]\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
